{"cursor":"3314","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Infobox officeholder |name = Lin Hsin-i æä¿¡ç¾© |other_name = |honorific-suffix\n= |image = |nationality = |order1 = |office1 = Vice Premier of the Republic of\nChina |premier1 = Yu Shyi-kun |term_start1 = 1 February 2002 |term_end1 = 20 May\n2004 |predecessor1 = Yeh Chu-lan |successor1 = Lai In-Jaw |order2 = |office2 =\nMinister of the Council for Economic Planning and Development of the Executive\nYuan |term_start2 = 1 February 2002 |term_end2 = 20 May 2004 |predecessor2 =\nChen Po-chih |successor2 = Hu Sheng-cheng |order3 = |office3 = Minister of\nEconomic Affairs of the Republic of China |term_start3 = 20 May 2000 |term_end3\n= 1 February 2002 |predecessor3 = Wang Chih-kang |successor3 = Christine Tsung\n|birth_date = |birth_place = Tainan, Taiwan |death_date = |death_place = |party\n= |alma_mater = National Cheng Kung University Oklahoma City University -\nhttp://taiwanreview.nat.gov.tw/ct.asp?xItem=524&CtNode=1347 |occupation =\nBusinessman |profession = }}\n\n\n'Lin Hsin-i' (), a Taiwanese businessman. He served in the Democratic\nProgressive Party administration as Minister of Economic Affairs between 2000\nand 2002, then as Vice Premier between 2002 and 2004.\n\nIn November 2005, while a Senior Presidential Adviser, Lin attended the Asia\nPacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum in Busan, South Korea, in place of\nTaiwan's President Chen Shui-bian. Because of opposition from the People's\nRepublic of China, Taiwan's senior leaders are unable to attend APEC events in\nperson and must send a ministerial-level envoy. He was Chairman of the\nIndustrial Technology Research Institute from 2004 to 2008.\n\nA graduate of National Cheng Kung University, Lin was an executive in the car\nindustry before entering politics.\n","linknr":199,"url":"Lin_Hsin-i","recorded":1375066106,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Lin_Hsin-i&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Lin_Hsin-i&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.o